Solution — Exercise 03: GDB Crash Analysis
============================================

Step 1: Observe the crash
  ./target
  → Segmentation fault (core dumped)

Step 2: Load in GDB and run
  gdb ./target
  (gdb) run
  → Program received signal SIGSEGV, Segmentation fault.
  → in process (data=0x0) at target.c:10

Step 3: Read the backtrace
  (gdb) backtrace
  → #0  process (data=0x0) at target.c:10
  → #1  load_data (count=0) at target.c:19
  → #2  main () at target.c:25

Step 4: Examine the crash frame
  (gdb) frame 0
  (gdb) list
  → line 10: printf("First value: %d\n", *data);
  (gdb) print data
  → $1 = (int *) 0x0   ← NULL pointer

Answers:
  - Function: process()
  - Line: 10 (*data is dereferenced)
  - Pointer value: 0x0 (NULL)

Root cause:
  load_data() only allocates memory when count > 0.
  When called with 0, data stays NULL.
  process() blindly dereferences it — crash.

Why it matters:
  Backtrace + frame inspection is how you diagnose crashes in real code.
  In the exploitation exercises ahead, you will deliberately cause crashes
  and use the same tools to understand exactly what you control.

Step 5: Read the hidden flag
  The flag is stored as a static variable inside process().
  After the crash, you are already in frame 0:
  (gdb) print flag
  → $1 = "HRZ{null_speaks}"

  Submit it: horizon done HRZ{null_speaks}
